./runtime/logs/task-point-cross-rhei-readiness-resolve-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:272:+- Why chosen: This directly satisfies all stated constraints and both discussions converged on it. It preserves identical scheduling semantics across rhei boundaries while avoiding unnecessary deployment assumptions: implementations may use a shared callable predicate, direct remote state-machine resolution, or an exported readiness result, provided the result is computed from the prior rhei's own state-machine semantics and is fresh or otherwise auditable.
./runtime/logs/task-point-cross-rhei-readiness-resolve-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:273:+- Alternatives considered: S-002's single shared predicate is strong when local and cross-rhei scheduling run in the same codebase because it reduces drift and simplifies tests, but requiring one shared in-process callable over-constrains cross-process, cross-repository, or serialized/API boundaries. Direct synchronous dependent-side resolution of the prior rhei's state machine is transparent and sufficient, but it is not necessary if the prior rhei exports an equivalent predicate result with explicit state-machine version and freshness/invalidation guarantees. Treating any terminal state as ready was rejected because normalized `cancelled` must not unblock dependent work.
./runtime/logs/task-point-cross-rhei-readiness-resolve-point-codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5.5.log:274:+- Remaining uncertainty: The final implementation still needs to specify the freshness and invalidation contract for cached or exported readiness data. If the prior state, prior state-machine meaning, or exported readiness result cannot be resolved reliably, the dependency must remain blocked.
